} random}} Playing Against the Computer
\par \pard\plain \s10\li120\sl-240 \f25\fs20\lang1033 
With Network DDE you can play against the computer in addition to playing against an opponent over the network.  The only problem with this is that the computer player is very dumb.  It just randomly selects holes into which to place pegs.  So don't expec
t a challenging game against this computer opponent. 
\par \pard\plain \li120\sb80\sl-240 \f25\fs20\lang1033 To play against the computer, select the {\uldb File New Game...}{\v new}{\b  }command from the menu.  In the dialog box select the middle radio button, "{\b Random Computer Player}," and then press the {
\b Okay }button.  {\b Net Gomuku} will start another version of its self which you will see as an icon at the bottom of the screen.  You can maximize the icon if you want to watch from the computer's perspective.
\par This feature was added to {\b Net Gomuku }to demonstrate that the same code which communicates over network DDE can also communicate over standard DDE.  When {\b Net Gomuku}
 plays against the computer it plays against another instance of itself over standard DDE.
\par The source code to Net Gomuku is avaliable on the Microsoft Developer Network CD, and writting a better computer player is left as an exercise to the reader.
